<h1>Tackling</h1>

<p>Learning the laws around the tackle allows you to avoid penalties and use techniques to avoid being tackled or to make better tackles.</p>

<img class="image" src="/Images/Tackle.jpg">

<h3>Tackle technique</h3>

<p>Let's be honest, tackling can be scary to a newcomer or junior player. Many new players are timid and reluctant to risk getting hurt by throwing their body in the way of a stampeding forward. It's ok in training, when you practise tackling at a jogging pace. However, in a match, the players are sprinting and they will try to fend you or bounce you off.</p>

<h5>Shoulder tackle</h5>

<p>There are several ways to tackle, but the most-effective method is to hit the ball carrier with your shoulder. You must keep your head safe, by positioning it behind the runner. Use your entire bodyweight and strength to drive your shoulder through them, pushing them sideways or backwards to the floor.</p>

<iframe class="video" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/CgCXCehf3xM" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>

<p>Notice how the ball carrier in the above video tries to bounce the tackler away using the ball. But the tackler drops to his knee and positions his shoulder below the ball, into the player's stomach. He then wraps his arms around the ball-carrier's leg and drives upwards, lifting the player off his feet and puts him on the ground safely. As a bonus, the tackler also dislodges the ball from the tackler's grip. His teammates congratulate him for causing the referee to award a scrum for a knock-on and relieving the pressure on their own line (it wasn't really a knock-on because the ball went backwards, but the referee is always right!).</p>

<h5>Wrap tackle</h5>

<p>If the ball-carrier is bigger than you or running so fast that you're worried you'll come off second best, then just wrap your arms around their waist, drop your body to the floor and hold on so that they're now dragging you along the ground. This may be enough to slow them down for one of your teammates to help push them to the ground. Think of tackling like catching a ball, but you're catching the player. Wrap them up and hold on or slide your grip down around their thighs and any player will either stop or fall over.</p>

<p>It's the tackler's duty to bring the ball-carrier to the ground safely. If you flip them over so that they land on their head, then you will be sent-off and banned for a few matches. Safety is very important.</p>

<h5>Chop tackle</h5>

