<p>There some excellent examples in the above video, but the clearest one is at 1:30, where England's juggernaut Manu Tuilagi only had to 5 metres to run to the tryline. However, Wales's Sam Warburton dives at Manu's ankles, effectively tripping him. Manu's own momentum brings him slamming to the floor.</p>

<h5>Dump tackle</h5>

<iframe class="video" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/ItvY-Gnr1rE?start=90" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>

<p>Just watch the video and enjoy.</p>

<p>This is the most exciting method of tackling. Commentators and pundits refer to these as dominant tackles. It's a shoulder tackle, but you don't immediately bring them to the ground. You lift them up and drive them backwards or even sideways over the touchline. These tackles will upset your opposition and lift your own team's morale. Be very careful that the ball carrier's hips aren't lifted above their head. The referee will call this "going beyond the horizontal" and you will be sent-off for doing it. This is the small difference between a great tackle and ruining the game by causing your team to play with just 14 players for the rest of the match.</p>

<h5>Tap tackle</h5>

<p>This is usually done as a last ditch attempt to stop a player from scoring. As you're chasing a player from behind, you dive forward to tap the ankle of their trailing leg. This causes their foot to hit the back of their other leg and they fall over. This technically isn't a tackle, because the ball-carrier isn't held, but it gives your teammates a chance to get back and tackle the player properly.</p>

