<h5>Man and ball</h5>

<p>When tackling, there's a risk that the ball-carrier will offload the ball to a teammate. Therefore, you should try to wrap the player, but also trap the ball, so they can't pass. You may even try to dislodge the ball from their grip. If this is done subtly, it can look like the player dropped it, meaning you could win a scrum. You can dislodge the ball using your hand, arm, or head (be very careful, of course).</p>

<h5>Understand the rules</h5>

<img class="image" src="/Images/ruck-3.jpg">

<p>A tackle has occurred when the ball-carrier has been brought to the ground. The ball carrier must also be held.</p>

<p>Being brought to the ground means that they are lying, sitting or one of their knees is on the ground or on another player, who is on the ground.</p>

<p>Being held means that the tackler must hold the ball-carrier until they're on the ground.</p>

<p>It's important to know these rules, because if you're not held in a tackle, you can jump to your feet and continue running.</p>

<p>So, what if you ARE held in the tackle? You must release the ball immediately.</p>

<p>But did you know that you can let go of the ball, jump to your feet, pick-up the ball and continue running? Just make sure the referee can clearly see you release the ball. Also, the tackler must release you. So if they don't, you win a penalty for your team.</p>

<iframe class="video" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/7bUm14pwgTg" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>

<h5>Release</h5>

<p>The tackler must release the tackled player and the ball and move out of the way or get to their feet without obstructing other players. They must allow the tackled player to move away too. Make sure you do this or you'll give away a penalty.</p>

<h5>Bad tackles</h5>

<p>A high tackle, above the armpits, is illegal. Using your feet or legs to trip a player or tackling a player without the ball is also illegal. You must also attempt to wrap your arms when you tackle, otherwise it's a shoulder charge.</p>

<p>You can tackle as hard as you like, but anything dangerous will be sanctioned by at least a penalty. You're also likely to be sin-binned or sent-off, leading to a lengthy ban. Professional players also receive hefty fines for dangerous play.</p>